{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507543"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2635"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2635"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.57,0.04,0.04,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2635"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44929"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2635"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2635"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29830"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3117"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35426"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44929"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 87-year-old man is being seen on the geriatrics ward. He was admitted with confusion and a urinary tract infection one day ago. In his assessment a determination will be made as to whether his current problem is one of dementia or delirium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following dynamics would be most useful in making this assessment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Memory","Attention","Communication","Understanding","Orientation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is often there is overlap in patients\u0027 presentation and demographic when considering dementia and delirium. The MMSE (mini mental state examination) is a commonly used cognitive tool to test patients. Both patients with dementia and those with delirium will often score on the lower end of this test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelirium is defined as an acute confusional state with the core features of inattention and global cognitive dysfunction. A differentiating factor between delirium and dementia is the fact that in delirium \u003Cstrong\u003Eattention\u003C/strong\u003E is impaired, whereas in dementia attention should not be impaired, unless very severe, as dementia has a greater impact on \u003Cstrong\u003Ememory\u003C/strong\u003E. The memory loss in dementia is often slow and progressive. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommunication\u003C/strong\u003E is often maintained in both conditions, but in severe cases can be compromised in both as well. Hence is not specific to either.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrientation\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a patient being aware of their location, name, time and date. This can be affected by various factors and is often affected in delirium, but not in all cases. It can also be affected in dementia when severe. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Eunderstanding\u003C/strong\u003E can be affected in both conditions but is non-specific.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the core characteristic for a diagnosis of delirium is a deficit in attention. This can be tested using the MMSE in the serial seven\u2019s test or spelling WORLD backwards. Dementia is characterised by deficits in memory, which can also be tested in aspects of the MMSE such as short term, medium and long-term recall.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A differentiating factor between delirium and dementia is the fact that in delirium attention is impaired, whereas in dementia attention should not be impaired, unless very severe, as dementia has a greater impact on memory."],"references":["Fong TG, Tulebaev SR, Inouye SK. Delirium in elderly adults: diagnosis, prevention and treatment. Nat Rev Neurol. 2009;5(4):210-220. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3065676/","Huang J. Overview of Delirium and Dementia. In: MSD Manual: Professional Version [online]. 2021. Available at: https://www.msdmanuals.com/en-au/professional/neurologic-disorders/delirium-and-dementia/overview-of-delirium-and-dementia.","European Delirium Association; American Delirium Society. The DSM-5 criteria, level of arousal and delirium diagnosis: inclusiveness is safer. BMC Med. 2014 Oct 8;12:141. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25300023/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2635"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-09T11:07:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T08:52:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2635"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44929"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdA